review_blob: Light and dry and funky, with a nice hoppiness backing it up. Good for drinking at shitty parties with your hoodrat friends.

Pours a thick, opaque black with a thin, foamy, khaki disk of head.
Faint spiciness in the nose. sweet. smells sticky and sugary.
Tastes pretty nice! spicy and creamy. lots of vanilla. Still really boozy, though. medium-full mouthfeel.

Holy crap. Hooooooly crap. Draft at the public house. Pours a dark, cloudy pink-purple. Thin head reasts on top and dissipates quickly. Taste and nose are dense with chocolate, vanilla, blackberry and raspberry. Sweet and fruity, creamy and yummy. Tastes just like Graeters Black Raspberry Chocolate Chunk ice cream. Medium-full body. drinks easily and REALLY sneaks up. It is easily my favorite beer Ive had in the past month. maybe in the past year.
beer_name: Jackie Os Bourbon Barrel Imperial Razz Wheat

review_blob: UPDATED: OCT 7, 2014

pours a hazy peach-flesh color with a frothy white head. smells creamy and sweet like lemon bars, with a touch of bracing pine, too. taste is banana, pineapple, coconut, and sweet, creamy citrus. pleasantly tart and fruity. pine butts in a little more than I might like, but overall this beer is damned impressive! I think if it was just rum barrels and not gin/rum barrels, I think this might be a bit better, but Im not even so sure about that. Tasty, thought-provoking beer.

opaque, inky black with a thin mocha head. the smell is quite powerful as soon as the cap was off. very vinous, but also roasty. smells sweet. tastes very creamy and sweet. nougat, chocolate, irish cream, cherry cordial. madeira. this is pretty yummy! especially considering that it was $5.99 per bomber at Country fresh. Right on!
beer_name: Sprecher Czar Brew Bourbon Barrel Imperial Stout

beer_brewer_name: Vermont Hard Cider Company, LLC (C&C; Group)
review_blob:
Couldnt resist it at the store. God knows what Im in for here. :P
pours an amber-burnt orange color with no head.

smells like non-alcoholic apple cider and cocoa puffs. not even- more like tootsie-roll-flavored novelty chapstick. like- super duper artificial. kind of an intriguing blend of charming and off-putting.

alright. its alright. I was expecting it to be something like this-
sweet baked apple and tootsie rolls. a little cinnamon. very sweet. caramelly and marshmallowy, too. this is fun.

light and spritzy. doesnt stick to ones throat or overstay its welcome.

this is silly, but I like it well enough, considering its a $5 bomber of chocolated flavored hard cider.

Dark brown body, cloudy to opaque. pours disturbingly soda-like. head fizzes up and then disappears into nothing in a matter of seconds. sinister.

strong aroma of tart apple liquor and cinnamon, and doughy french toast type sweetness/warmth. The apple seems... unintentional, but it smells nice anyway, though its pretty distracting. boozy, too.

yeesh- the apple is really overwhelmig, and its hot as hell, too. I dont think I can recommend this one.
beer_name: Dark Horse Bourbon Barrel Aged Louies Long Polymer John Donut Ale

review_blob: Pours black with a tan head. smells like a very big black IPA, more than anything- very roasty and piney. A little bakers chocolate and petrichor, too. Tastes very hoppy and piney with a lot of nice, bitter chocolate, too. Finishes sweet. The alcohol hides very well.

Pours a medium-dark copper color with a thin tan head. Smells like toffee and vanilla. taste is sweet and creamy with just a hint of hoppy bitterness to pull it back from being cloying. Mouthfeel is sticky and thick, but I dont feel like Im gonna choke on it or anything. This beer. This fucking beer right here. Good stuff. Very good. One of my favorite barleywines ever.
This stuff is outta sight. Not trying to put up a full review right now, but I Like this one a lot and will revisit it in the future for sure.

Now this is a good-ass beer. Its like biting into a powdered, freshly baked, dark-chocolate eclair, with a kahlua-infused custard filling. also, theres a hint of almond to it, too. the mouthfeel is just like chocolate milk. its super comforting and pleasant!
beer_name: Dark Horse Bourbon Barrel Plead the 5th Imperial Stout

review_blob: Reviewed in the dark with a congested nose. So sue me. I get a lot of cranberry and lime from this one. a lot of really intriguing bitter fruit notes. the full body and sweetness stands up to the dry and bitter cranberryish notes. Dry finish. I like this one.
Sweet and peppery. Floral and a little spicy. Very smooth, too. I liked this one pretty well! Maybe not like- mindblowing, but I think its extremely pleasant. Pleasant is a good word for this beer.

On tap at Cinci Craft Beer Oktoberfest. Pours black with a thin brown disk on top. Coffee and vanilla in the nose. Medium roast. Smells nice. Sweet. This is pretty tasty- Apparent coffee. Earthy and roasty. Bittersweet. Full mouthfeel, medium carb. Wanna see more like this.

Excellent smoothness, subtle barrel character. This is really well executed, I think.

pours a cloudy gold color with a fluffy white head. Almost looks like orange juice. Taste is clean. Biscuity malt, a little bit of orange peel flavor. Herby bitterness. Aroma is herbal and citrusy as well. It was refreshing, but it was kind of hard to finish. Refreshing and light, but also somewhat harsh and low on flavor all at once. Worth a try, but it kind of falls in with Southern tiers other pale stuff in that its kind of forgettable.

Pours a spritsy, clear golden yellow with a foamy white head. Starts at about a centimeter and recedes to a super thin disk gradually but quickly.
Smells pretty boozy. Hoppy, too. Resiny and piney. A little floral. Almost... a honeycomb... kind of sweetness. Smells... like you could sterilize surgical tools in it.This tastes a lot sweeter than Id expected. Lots of honey to it. I like how the alcohol burn feels in the mouth. Spirit-like. This is a pretty remarkable beer. Maybe not great, but remarkable in a "Makes me feel like remarking on it" kind of way. Whiew...its a little like shochu in the finish... Very clean. Very dry. 

>_____< 

But woof- that alcohol is... palpable.
beer_name: Mikkeller / To l Walk on Water

review_blob: Pours inky black with a 1 cm mocha head- layered with foamy little bubbles on top and big, darker bubbles on bottom. Classic. loads of dark fruit and creamy vanilla in the nose. medium roast coffee, toffee, and chocolate fudge, too. Super sweet smell. Sooo creamy. This is the creamiest beer Ive ever had. Super smooth- the whisky comes through in a big way; wine less so, but still present. Loads of creamy mocha, caramel, whisky and spice... I dont know, man- this is blowing my mind. Gonna have to get more of it. Shout out to Dr.Silverworm for the recommendation. Always appreciate it.

Pours golden with a thick, white head. funky, slightly bourbony nose. I get vanilla, leathery funk, and cream, mostly. Doesnt smell or taste too sour. Mostly like a nice, funky, wild Belgian Strong Pale. Bourbony Flemish Primitive, almost. I like this one. Creamy and bourbony, but only just enough. It doesnt overpower the other elements. Bitter, spicy, a little bit of sweetness and creaminess to it, too. I think that this is pretty darn good, despite the extremely unfortunate name. Why somebody would name a beer after smelly ass is completely beyond me. Hats off to quaff bros. for another interesting and well executed barrel-aged beer.

Pours black with a thick tan head. Mint is evident in the nose. Dark chocolate. Mint is pretty good in this- chocolate mint and a touch of coffee. This stuff is nice! Much less harsh than any other mint stout Ive had. I dont know if the mint really adds too much to the Plead the 5th, but this was fun to try.

Sampled at Big Beers and Barleywines Datyon

3 Pairs of Legs, Bourbon Barrel-Aged Maple Shake, whatever its called. I think this is the right listing.

Chocolate brown pour. Thin, off-white ring of head. Very sweet, sugary maple smell with lots of chocolate, too. Vanilla, caramel, lots of very clear bourbon barrel character. Super mellow and slick. Suuuuper smooth. Chocolatey, creamy, loads of maple, bourbon, vanilla. Exceptional, I think. I had to go back for a few more pours of this one.

Sampled at Big Beers and Barleywines Dayton.
beer_name: Dark Horse 3 Pairs Of Legs Maple Porter

review_blob: s/o to DrSilverworm for the share. Translucent dark brown,fluffy tan head. Intense coffee smell and taste- almost... Hmm. Very roasty. Yes. Charcoal? Maybe not, but I reserve that for later. Smells burnt. I like that sometimes. This is one such time. Sweet. Roasty. Bitter. I wanna see more coffee browns. In stouts, sometimes its just too much. I thinkbrown ales are just right for coffee. Smooth, rich, creamy mouthfeel. Not that bad!
beer_name: 8 Wired C4 Double Coffee Brown Ale

review_blob:
"Its Reeses for breakfast!"

Thats it. Thats all I have written down here.

Shared with DrSilverworm. Cloudy brownish red. White lacing. Smells very fruity with raisins, figs, and dates at the front. Smells vinegary and creamy, too. Faint medicinal/herbal scent. Black cherry in the taste supported by raisin, date and fig notes. Tart. Balsamic, but also quite sweet. Well balanced, even now. Almost chocolatey at times. Neat! Spritzy and effervescent. Good bitterness. Hint of bubblegum? Hmm... Pretty singular stuff. If you can find it, its definitely worth a try.

Shared with DrSilverworm. Brilliant gold hue. Thin, foamy, bone-white head. Visible bubbles. Woody and vinous smell. Very citrusy, too. Pink Grapefruit and blood orange. Smells yummy! Taste follows smell in a big way- leathery and funky, too. Bready, Bretty. Nice blend of gentle tartness and sweet fruitiness, but I think a little more bitterness would push this in a more interesting direction? Dunno. The individual elements are awesome, but some of them feel like theyre just outside of the perfect ratio. What do I know, though. Very light mouthfeel. Creamy. Gentle carbonation.
Shared with DrSilverworm. Cloudy burnt orange body with a creamy head. Creamy and perfumey. Floral. Sweet... almost tea-like. Smooth. A little sticky. Medium body. I dont mind this.

Shared with DrSilverworm. Pours inky dark brown with mocha head. .75cm. recedes slowly into lace. Smells roasty. Charred. Almost smoky. Loads of coffee. Deep-ass shit. Smells good. Slick and smooth. Medium body. Coffee flavor. A little dark fruit. Niiiiice. Touch of dark chocolate. "Roasty, almost smokey" keeps coming back to mind. This is tasty. Lighter carbonation than I was expecting. Creamy.

Shared with DrSilverworm. "Fuckin look at THAT!" Kool-aid pink body with a white head. recedes quickly to a little ring. big raspberry and an almost yoghurty creamy tartness. sweet, creamy and tart in the nose. Auspicious start for me here.Taste follows the nose- wheaty, light adn refreshing. Yummy! Jammy and still creamy. Light carb. s/o to Josh S. for hooking me up with this bottle.

s/o to DrSilverworm for the share. pours cloudy dark brownish orange. Red? Purple? Whos been fucking with my medicine? 1.5cm head recedes quickly to a tiny tiny ring. agitation restores it to a thin pancake. Creamy fruit and molasses in the nose. This smells gooooood. Mmmmmmmmm That is juicy. Extremely smooth and creamy. Fruity and sweet- molasses, too. Oh dude- thanks for sharing this one. It is good. 2012 vintage.
beer_name: Southern Tier Oak Aged Back Burner

review_blob: s/o to DrSilverworm for the share. Golden yellow, white little head recedes quickly. Hmmm... Pineapple in the nose. Bretty. Tastes like it smells. Not as hoppy as "hoppy farmhouse ale" would seem to suggest. Light and fizzy. finishes kinda slick and unctuous. Not bad at all. That finish feels kinda whack, though. Pours hazy at the end. Juicy and fruity.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: s/o to Dr.Silverworm for the share. Golden yellow body with a white head. About 1cm. Recedes quickly into a ring. agitation restores it to about calf a cm. Smells sweet and flowery. Orange. Sweet citrus. Tastes very... insubstantial. Like the nose, but toned down. Flowery but a little bitter, too. warms up and comes better into the flavors in the nose but doesnt do anything terribly exciting or unexpected. Mouthfeel is light-medium thickness. Tingly. In a weird way.

Shared by Pixachii. (Thanks, Miss!) Pours a clear golden color. Head fluffs up to about one inch. Smells lagery, but really dragged through the hop garden. Very fruity and perfumey, this one. Not a ton to say about the taste, really- Its got that lagery smoothness and sweetness, but with more fruity, floral notes and bitterness to it, too. Refreshing. Hoppy. Big flavor, but still extremely drinkable. I think this did exactly what they wanted it to. I dont mind this!

Shared with Pixachii. Pours a clear golden yellow color with a thin white disk on top, recedes to lace in seconds. Smells tart and funky. Fruity. Lemon. Wet stone. Wheat. Honey. Tastes tart. Very tart, in fact. Still with the honey and wheat. Very lemony and fruity. Interesting- tastes more like a little lambic than a Berliner, really. Light, fizzy, and extremely drinkable.
UPDATED: MAR 26, 2013

Bottle shared with Pixachii. Pours a clear brass color with a fluffy white head. recedes to a thin disk and retains. Intense floral and resiny aroma. I love it. Smells extremely sweet too, with orange flesh and perfumey grapefruit notes. Intense bitterness rushes everywhere and coats the palate. Piney and floral and perfumey. Theres a kind of fruity, juicy sweetness in there that finds some balance with the bitterness, but only just. This is my very favorite double IPA.

Shared with Pixachii. Pours inky black with a creamy, mocha head. Leaves brownish oil trailing down the glass. Small bubbles- frothy. Recedes to a thin pancake and retains. Smells like walnut and coffee. Big aromas of dark cocoa, coffee, nuts- but all balanced so its not overpowering. Drinks super smooth. Super creamy. I cant stop drinking it. Chocolatey mocha and walnutty goodness. Medium-full body with good sweet-bitter balance. I seriously cant put it down. Send help.
UPDATED: MAR 25, 2013
UPDATED: MAR 26, 2013

Golden, slightly coudy body. Egg-shell head: 2.5 fingers. Recedes to sticky ring with lots of lacing. Agitation restores it to about 1 finger. Funky, oaky, tannic. VERY lemony. mmmm. A little persimmon and what I can only describe as "wet cork." Lemony tartness, very tannic and bitter. Bone-dry finish. I love this stuff.

Nearly opaque peachy orange. Looks really pretty.
Faint citrus(grapefruit stands out) and funk. Wood.
Sweet, sour, and vinous with lots of citrus and tropical fruit, particularly grapefruit, lemon, passion fruit, and pineapple. Finishes with bitter pink grapefruit and oaky funk. Dry as a bone.
Id love to get another taste of this, but I doubt Ill ever see it again. Rats!

One of the most orange looking beers Ive ever had. Verges on Gatorade-like. An aggressive pour yielded a healthy looking head that disappeared within about a minute.
Pumpkin and a little malt. Straight up. You may think I mean pumpkin pie. I dont. Just pumpkin. The raw, fruiting body of plants from the Cucurbita genus.
Very odd. Seems to focus more on the plant itself, rather than the spices that complement it. Theyre there, but the raw pumpkin itself is center stage. Its very malty and sweet with intense pumpkin flavor, but the spices dont come out in a big way until the finish.
Id seen this one all over the place and had been meaning to give it a try. Its certainly something unusual; the malt and raw pumpkin flavors seem to give this beer a sort of dual nature- sweet and mellow, but bright and fruity. Its interesting beer, but Im not quite sure what to make of it.

Somewhat cloudy brass body, two-finger bone-white head. good retention.
Beauuuutiful. Perfumey floral and citrus hop notes. You can smell it at arms length. Just gorgeous.
Perfect level of sweetness with just enough bitterness to balance it. 
Amazingly smooth. The carbonation is present but unobtrusive.
This has got to be one of the best American IPAs out there today. I adore this beer.

(2011 Vintage. Consumed fresh. Reviewed from notes.)

Pitch black body, light tan head.
Bourbon up front, with chocolate, caramel, and vanilla.
The bourbon is there, but doesnt overpower the other flavors. Rather it complements them very nicely. Chocolatey, caramely, loads of vanilla- even nearing half an hour after tasting it, its like I just finished an ice-cream sundae.
Low carbonation, smooth. A little on the thin side, certainly for the style.
This is one of the better BB Stouts Ive had from this area. Im looking forward to seeing what else the folks at Listermanns will come out with in the future.

Inky black body with a layered dark and milk chocolate head.
Mmm- lots of coffee and chocolate in the nose.
Intense mocha flavor, with coffee leading and chocolate supporting.
Thick and warming, with with a slight (almost) gritty feeling induced by the light carbonation.
Its super creamy and decadent. Ill have to try baking with this someday.

This is the kind of beer that I REALLY shouldnt like, but theres just no helping me sometimes; this tastes just fine to me. Tastes and smells like honey kvass with hops added. It finishes a bit like a bourbon whisky; corny, grainy and a little woody- bracing, but it invites you back in. Nearly amber in color- looks like cheap maple syrup straight from the microwave. This is what I buy when I want to get VERY drunk VERY quickly and not have too much to complain about as far as taste (its a little like drinking a loaf of bread, soggy with hard liquor). It warms you up like no other. Gotta be good for that Russian winter.

Two finger, fluffy off-white head recedes to about a half finger and retains admirably. Burnt orange, dark amber body.
Sweet and fruity nose with zesty hop notes, too. Almost like iced tea.
Sweet, creamy, and flavorful. Full bodied. Fruity, spicy, bitter, and tea-like. Drinks soooo easily.
I love this stuff.

1.5 finger off-white head, recedes quickly; brass body, unclouded, but with floaties. Not pretty, but I dont really mind.
Floral and fruity hop aroma (Odd notes Im getting: white grapes and coriander). Smells yummy.
Citrusy, piney, herbal. So on, so forth. It tastes fine, but doesnt really distinguish itself very much in any way. Thin and dry.
Its alright.
UPDATED: JAN 30, 2013

Dark burnt orange-reddish body. White head, one finger.
Rich creamy pumpkin spiciness, alcohol. Mmmmm. I like how this one smells.
Verrrry toasty and sweet. Good balance between the spice and pumpkin flavor. Sweet, but not terribly cloying. Medium bodied, light carbonation.
Not too shabby. I wouldnt say it beats out Pumking, but this stuff is tasty and cheap. Get you some.
beer_name: Samuel Adams Fat Jack Double Pumpkin

review_blob: Pours a clear golden yellow. Big head, really- about 2.5 fingers. Retention is really impressive, too. It reduced to a ring over time, but it still looks good. Fluffy. Nice lacing. Uncharacteristic for the style, and certainly for the ABV. When I first poured it, all I could get was cornmeal, wet slate, and fusel alcohol, but as it warmed up- okay, this is weird, but I got a lot of really nice grape/raisin notes and some nuttiness, too. Still with corniness, but pleasant. Impressive. Woah! Okay- super sweet and a little spicy. A little bite to it, but not so unpleasant. The alcohol doesnt actually make a nuisance of itself. Kind of peanutty and grapey... White raisins... Corn as well, but like in the nose, not so unpleasant or out of control. It almost tastes like an abt. A good one. Quelle bizarre. Extremely smooth for what it is and how high the abv is. Light carbonation. Medium-full body. Very drinkable, unqualified with any sort of "*for an 11% malt liquor" footnotes. This just drinks well. This was really impressive and Im hoping to find it again some day. A year and some change must have done it a world of good, looking at these other reviews, because this isnt bad at all, Id say.
